:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/D002982/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The challenge addressed in this research is to explain how culture (ie the learned component in human behaviour) can be understood as something constantly changing.&amp;nbsp;This is a challenge to anthropologists because they often assume that culture is acquired in childhood and has an unchanging, ahistorical nature. The chief idea here is that people acquire language, values, customs and so forth as tools for persuading themselves and others of appropriate behaviour among the rapid changes of social life.&amp;nbsp;Another way to put this is to say that, because human beings have a particularly intense and changeable form of sociality, they use cultural learning to deal with emergencies arising in the process of social interaction.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The first part of the project involves showing how this so-called rhetoric culture theory can improve on other theories which have addressed similar issues.&amp;nbsp;The second part of the project involves field research in East Germany, which has been a site of especially rapid social change in the present generation.&amp;nbsp;Here the research will concentrate on 1) the creation of new publics&amp;nbsp;which have arisen after the fall of the Berlin Wall, and 2) on new forms of personhood which have also risen in that period.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>356242</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>7B783530-4FF3-426A-B575-7B733AE051C3</gtr:id><gtr:title>From Inchoate Pronouns to Proper Nouns: A Theory Fragment with 9/11, Gertrude Stein, and an East German Ethnography</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>History and Anthropology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/89630c5b25d4e215250ee673cf36b2a3"><gtr:id>89630c5b25d4e215250ee673cf36b2a3</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Carrithers M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cf99f99b515b32</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifie